\C{overview} Overview and highlights

lDebug is a 86-DOS debugger based on the MS-DOS Debug clone FreeDOS Debug.
It features DPMI client support for 32-bit and 16-bit segments,
a 686-level assembler and disassembler, an expression evaluator,
an InDOS and a bootloaded mode, script file reading, serial port I/O,
permanent breakpoints, conditional tracing, buffered tracing,
and auto-repetition of some commands.
There is also a symbolic debugging option being developed.


\H{quickstart} Quick start for reading this manual

\b The interface reference explains the basics of the debugger's interface
and lists some common commands.

\b The parameter reference lists the types of parameters
used by the available commands.

\b The command reference describes most commands in detail.

\b The expression reference details how numeric parameters
are parsed by the expression evaluator.

\b The variable reference lists a subset of the debugger's variables
and what they can be used for.

\b The interrupt reference lists what interrupt hooks the debugger sets up.

\b The service reference lists what services are called by the debugger,
which may be useful for developers of the debugger,
or of kernels, ROM-BIOSes, or DPMI hosts.

\b The online help pages provide some additional descriptions
not found elsewhere in the manual,
as well as overviews of many different topics.

\b The command help lists most of the switches and parameters
accepted by the debugger and the instsect program.

\b The news lists an overview of changes since prior releases of lDebug.

\b Invoking the debugger states how to start the debugger,
either bootloaded, as a device driver, as an application,
or through the test suite.

\b Building the debugger lists components, build options,
and instructions on how to build.

\b Debugging the debugger itself lists some considerations
for working with CDebug or DDebug as a debuggee.

\b The additional usage conditions section lists
attribution and licenses for the various depackers
that can be used for the compressed debugger executable.

\b Source Control Revision ID gives the Mercurial hash
of the manual's source revision,
and links to that revision in ecm's repository.

For a tour, definitely start with the interface reference.
To help invoke the debugger read the section on
\q{Invoking the debugger as an application}.
It may help to read the manual while testing the debugger on another terminal.
Use the main page of the online help as a reference to what is possible,
then check the command reference for details.
To explain what parameter types are used refer to the parameter reference.
For how to calculate refer to the expression reference.

Reconfiguring the debugger can be done using variables,
including the \cw{Debugger Assembler Options} (DAO) and
the \cw{Debugger Common Options} (DCO) 1 to 6.
Use the variable reference and the online help pages on the options for those.
Change variables using the R commands,
such as \cq{r dco or= 800} or \cq{r ior := #50}.


\H{tips} Some tips for using the debugger


\b Use the \cw{GT} or \cw{GNT} commands to skip past conditionals

\b Use \cw{G ABO} to skip past calls or loops if \cw{P} would not work

\b T, P, G, U, and D commands have autorepeat
to repeat the same command if an empty line (only blanks) is entered
after they return control to the debugger prompt

\b The \cw{POINTER} type expression allows
using a 32-bit number as a 16:16 segmented address
whereever an address parameter is parsed

\b The assembler can access the expression evaluator
by surrounding an expression with parentheses \cq{(...)}

\b The A, E, D, and U commands write to the AAO, AEO, ADO, and AUO variables
to point past the end of their last read or write

\b The ABO variable points past the last instruction
disassembled by an R command

\b Permanent breakpoints can be set up using the B commands,
including as pass points or conditionally

\b The G command can repeat the prior list
by specifying the \cw{AGAIN} keyword as the first breakpoint,
and can save to the list without actually executing the debuggee
by ending the breakpoint list with a \cw{REMEMBER} keyword

\b T, P, and G commands can change either the instruction pointer only
or also the code segment using
an equals-sign-prefixed address as the first prameter.
The TTEST command will change the CS:IP without actually executing anything.

\b The machine type can be viewed or changed with an M command.
Assembly and disassembly will note if a required machine level
is absent according to the machine type.

\b DCO option 800 enables the line editor and input history
even when using DOS for input

\b DCO6 option 200 will use the ROM-BIOS for output instead of DOS,
including for register change highlighting

\b DCO option 8 will act as if the debugger is
always running with the InDOS flag set,
avoiding DOS calls from the debugger itself

\b The \cw{INSTALL AMIS} and \cw{INSTALL TIMER} commands
can be used to provide the debugger's AMIS interface
and hook the timer interrupt

\b The \cw{DW ss:sp} command is useful
to view the current stack formatted as words

\b The debugger is largely capitalisation-insensitive

\b The LFSR variable allows to generate a stream of pseudo-random numbers

\b The DIM command shows MCB names of blocks pointed to by interrupt vectors,
while DIL (or DIML) will query AMIS multiplexers
for their interrupt entrypoints to find hidden chains

\b Long output of many commands is paged by default,
displaying a \cq{[more]} prompt that
pauses the output until a keypress is received

\b The VALUE IN construct allows to match one numeric value or range
against many match values or match ranges

\b A breakpoint can be set up on an interrupt handler
by issuing for example \cq{BP NEW ptr ri2Dp},
if the interrupt handler is writeable

\b If given a single expression the H command
displays the result as hexadecimal and as decimal

\b Decimal numbers can be entered with a \cw{#} prefix,
and binary with \cw{2#}.
Character codes can be used as numbers with \cw{#"..."}

\b Script files can be run with the Y command

\b A program can be traced until it tries
to modify interrupts 1 or 3 using
\cq{tp FFFFF while ! value from linear 0:1*4 length 3*4 in writing silent}.
Add a conditional breakpoint
like \cq{bp new ptr ri21p when value ax in 2501, 2503} beforehand
to intercept DOS calls to change these interrupts

\b If at its entrypoint and you want to return from a near function,
use \cq{g word [ss:sp]}.
For a 16-bit far or interrupt function use \cq{g ptr [ss:sp]}

\b In a loop with several exit conditons,
trace with T or P and accumulate exits
with \cq{G AGAIN address REMEMBER}
(insert an offset or \cw{(NOT)TAKEN} keywords for the address),
then finally run \cq{G AGAIN}

\b The L and W commands for reading and writing sectors
accept drive letters for their second parameter,
specified with a trailing colon

\b The RV, RVM, RVP, and RVD commands will show some information
on modes, memory segment locations, processes, and device headers

\b RX toggles the 32-bit register view for the R command

\b The RE buffer can contain many different commands,
which are run on RE commands or when T, P, or G initiate a register dump

\b The DCO options are described in the full \cw{?O} help page
as well as individual pages like \cw{?O6} for DCO6

\b Not sure what version of lDebug is running?
The command \cw{?BUILD} displays the description
and source control revision IDs.
The description includes a build date or release number.

\b Setting a breakpoint at the current instruction pointer with the G command
will trace past this instruction once
then write the breakpoint and run at full speed

\b There's a TSR mode converting the application-mode debugger
into a resident program, allowing to debug the debugger's parent process

\b The symbolic F register for the R command
allows dumping and modifying the flags using the abbreviated flag states

\b The R command can modify variables
using binary operators suffixed by an equal sign,
both on the command line of the R command
as well as after the R variable prompt

\b By adding a trailing dot after a variable name for the R command,
a variable's value can be inspected
without bringing up a variable prompt
that requires submitting a second input line


