\H{helpc} ?C - Conditionals

In the register dump displayed by the R, T, P and G commands, conditional
jumps are displayed with a notice that shows whether the instruction will
cause a jump depending on its condition and the current register and flag
contents. This notice shows either "jumping" or "not jumping" as appropriate.

The conditional jumps use these conditions: (second column negates)

\c  jo             jno             OF
\c  jc jb jnae     jnc jnb jae     CF
\c  jz je          jnz jne         ZF
\c  jbe jna        jnbe ja         ZF||CF
\c  js             jns             SF
\c  jp jpe         jnp jpo         PF
\c  jl jnge        jnl jge         OF^^SF
\c  jle jng        jnle jg         OF^^SF || ZF
\c  j(e)cxz                        (e)cx==0
\c  loop                           (e)cx!=1
\c  loopz loope                    (e)cx!=1 && ZF
\c  loopnz loopne                  (e)cx!=1 && !ZF

Enter ?F to display a description of the flag names.


\H{helpe} ?E - Expressions

Recognized operators in expressions:

\c |       bitwise OR              ||      boolean OR
\c ^       bitwise XOR             ^^      boolean XOR
\c &       bitwise AND             &&      boolean AND
\c >>      bit-shift right         >       test if above
\c >>>     signed bit-shift right  <       test if below
\c <<      bit-shift left          >=      test if above-or-equal
\c ><      bit-mirror              <=      test if below-or-equal
\c +       addition                ==      test if equal
\c -       subtraction             !=      test if not equal
\c *       multiplication          =>      same as >=
\c /       division                =<      same as <=
\c %       modulo (A-(A/B*B))      <>      same as !=
\c **      power

Implicit operater precedence is handled in the listed order, with increasing
precedence: (Brackets specify explicit precedence of an expression.)

\c  boolean operators OR, XOR, AND (each has a different precedence)
\c  comparison operators
\c  bitwise operators OR, XOR, AND (each has a different precedence)
\c  shift and bit-mirror operators
\c  addition and subtraction operators
\c  multiplication, division and modulo operators
\c  power operator

Recognized unary operators: (modifying the next number)

\c +       positive (does nothing)
\c -       negative
\c ~       bitwise NOT
\c !       boolean NOT
\c ?       absolute value
\c !!      convert to boolean

Note that the power operator does not affect unary operator handling.
For instance, "- 2 ** 2" is parsed as "(-2) ** 2" and evaluates to 4.

Although a negative unary and signed bit-shift right operator are provided
the expression evaluator is intrinsically unsigned. Particularly the division,
multiplication, modulo and all comparison operators operate unsigned. Due to
this, the expression "-1 < 0" evaluates to zero.

Recognized terms in an expression:

\c  32-bit immediates
\c  8-bit registers
\c  16-bit registers including segment registers (except FS, GS)
\c  32-bit compound registers made of two 16-bit registers (eg DXAX)
\c  32-bit registers and FS, GS only if running on a 386+
\c  32-bit variables V00..VFF
\c  32-bit special variables DCO, DCS, DAO, DAS, DIF, DPI, PPI
\c  16-bit special variables DPR, DPP, PSP, PPR
\c   (fuller variable reference in the manual)
\c  byte/word/3byte/dword memory content (eg byte [seg:ofs], where both the
\c   optional segment as well as the offset are expressions too)

The expression evaluator case-insensitively checks for names of variables
and registers as well as size specifiers.

Enter ?R to display the recognized register names.
Enter ?V to display the recognized variables.


